01:32:59,299 --> 01:33:04,532
See, when the player sits down
at the table, the software, it reads this...

1194
01:33:04,638 --> 01:33:06,105
Biometric profile.

1195
01:33:06,206 --> 01:33:07,969
...biometric profile of your face,

1196
01:33:08,075 --> 01:33:11,100
cross-references it
with a database of counters.

1197
01:33:14,647 --> 01:33:19,448
Software'll probably put you and me
out of business, but it still can't do this.

1198
01:33:22,622 --> 01:33:23,919
All right.

1199
01:33:29,495 --> 01:33:32,362
You understand all this. You go to MIT.

1200
01:33:32,732 --> 01:33:34,131
Smart boy.

1201
01:33:35,601 --> 01:33:37,535
My name is Cole Williams.

1202
01:33:38,137 --> 01:33:41,402
And if I ever see you in this town again,

1203
01:33:42,175 --> 01:33:45,576
I will break your cheek bone
with a small hammer,

1204
01:33:46,813 --> 01:33:48,804
and then I will kill you.

1205
01:33:53,486 --> 01:33:57,047
Please. Please just take the money.

1206
01:33:58,291 --> 01:33:59,815
You can take it.

1207
01:34:02,528 --> 01:34:03,859
Tell me,

1208
01:34:04,430 --> 01:34:09,163
how's good old Professor Rosa doing, huh?

1209
01:34:10,837 --> 01:34:15,433
Oh, yeah. Me and Micky, we go way back.

1210
01:34:16,542 --> 01:34:19,533
I spent years, chased him all over this town.

1211
01:34:19,978 --> 01:34:24,938
Giving him beat downs left and right,
only to find him at the tables a week later.

1212
01:34:25,050 --> 01:34:27,018
He was very persistent.

1213
01:34:27,919 --> 01:34:31,218
And then, one September night,

1214
01:34:31,723 --> 01:34:34,624
when I was in Barstow
at my father's funeral,

1215
01:34:35,494 --> 01:34:38,930
my casino was taken for seven figures.

1216
01:34:39,030 --> 01:34:40,361
Can you imagine that?

1217
01:34:40,465 --> 01:34:43,696
The most ever taken by a single counter
in one night.

1218
01:34:43,802 --> 01:34:48,398
'Course I was, naturally,
unceremoniously fired.

1219
01:34:51,109 --> 01:34:52,872
Funny thing, though.

1220
01:34:53,278 --> 01:34:55,803
I never saw Micky Rosa after that.

1221
01:34:56,982 --> 01:34:58,108
Never.

1222
01:36:24,835 --> 01:36:26,962
<i>Cauchy was the first
to make a rigorous study</i>

1223
01:36:27,071 --> 01:36:31,098
of the conditions for convergence
of an infinite series.

1224
01:36:31,208 --> 01:36:33,506
And was concerned with developing

1225
01:36:33,611 --> 01:36:38,480
the basic theorems of the calculus
as rigorously as possible.

1226
01:36:39,883 --> 01:36:41,315
Any questions?

1227
01:36:41,718 --> 01:36:43,845
No? All right, moving on.

1228
01:36:44,887 --> 01:36:48,880
Isn't it true Cauchy stole from his students?

1229
01:36:53,796 --> 01:36:57,664
Yes, I heard that.
What's your theory on that?

1230
01:36:58,701 --> 01:37:03,229
They say he used his students
for their brilliance,

1231
01:37:04,374 --> 01:37:08,606
then discredited them
and stole their equations,

1232
01:37:10,680 --> 01:37:12,545
stole their hard work.

1233
01:37:15,251 --> 01:37:17,947
Well, that wouldn't be the first time
a teacher was accused of that.

1234
01:37:18,054 --> 01:37:22,753
I think what he's referring to
is Vladimir Stupnitsky, yes?

1235
01:37:22,859 --> 01:37:25,794
He was a student of Cauchy's
who accused Cauchy

1236
01:37:25,895 --> 01:37:29,228
of stealing his four-volume text
on this analysis

1237
01:37:29,332 --> 01:37:31,800
and publishing it under a pseudonym.

1238
01:37:33,636 --> 01:37:35,297
Of course, nobody knows
what really went down there.

1239
01:37:35,405 --> 01:37:39,398
They never did prove it, and without
the proof, it's a little like it never happened.

1240
01:37:39,509 --> 01:37:41,534
And, you know, it's a real shame,

1241
01:37:41,644 --> 01:37:45,842
because if Stupnitsky had just realized
that he shouldn't have crossed Cauchy,

1242
01:37:45,948 --> 01:37:47,677
this was the dispute,

1243
01:37:48,718 --> 01:37:54,713
if he'd been able to get beyond some
of the personal mistakes that were made,

1244
01:37:55,257 --> 01:37:58,488
I have no doubt that Cauchy
would have worked with him again,

1245
01:37:58,593 --> 01:38:01,619
and they could have
done great things together.

1246
01:38:02,030 --> 01:38:06,091
But, as history shows us,
some students never learn.

1247
01:38:07,803 --> 01:38:09,464
You should get that eye looked at.

1248
01:38:46,675 --> 01:38:48,074
You okay?

1249
01:38:51,046 --> 01:38:52,673
Everything's gone.

1250
01:38:54,483 --> 01:38:57,077
- What?
- Micky's taken everything.

1251
01:38:57,185 --> 01:39:01,417
He's taken the money,
taken away Harvard Med, even MIT.

1252
01:39:03,290 --> 01:39:05,383
- What are you talking about?
- Micky, he's taken everything.

1253
01:39:05,493 --> 01:39:07,893
I gotta find a way to get it back.

1254
01:39:09,196 --> 01:39:10,686
Are you insane?

1255
01:39:11,298 --> 01:39:14,859
You just got the shit kicked out of you
and you won't let this go!

1256
01:39:14,969 --> 01:39:18,905
Look, what am I supposed to do, Jill?
I've just lost everything!

1257
01:39:19,673 --> 01:39:21,163
Look, please...

1258
01:39:22,977 --> 01:39:25,241
I don't want to lose you, too.

1259
01:39:28,249 --> 01:39:31,844
Ben, you were dragged away in Vegas.

1260
01:39:32,520 --> 01:39:36,854
I haven't heard from you.
I had no idea where you were.

1261
01:39:37,558 --> 01:39:38,786
I know.

1262
01:39:39,760 --> 01:39:40,920
I know.

1263
01:39:48,269 --> 01:39:51,067
You know, I'm so sorry that I hurt you.

1264
01:39:52,873 --> 01:39:54,238
I'm sorry.

1265
01:39:57,111 --> 01:40:01,605
In Vegas, I don't know what happened.
That wasn't me.

1266
01:40:02,817 --> 01:40:04,444
Look, you know me.

1267
01:40:05,152 --> 01:40:07,017
You know what I'm like.

1268
01:40:08,823 --> 01:40:10,313
You know me.

1269
01:40:16,763 --> 01:40:18,628
I need you to trust me.

1270
01:40:19,966 --> 01:40:23,333
<i>And the winner of this year's 2.09</i>

1271
01:40:23,436 --> 01:40:29,705
<i>for excellence in the field of robotics
goes to the team of Conolly and Kazazi!</i>

1272
01:41:07,080 --> 01:41:10,049
That's it. That's the story.

1273
01:41:12,552 --> 01:41:14,782
Jill Taylor. Really?

1274
01:41:15,588 --> 01:41:19,080
- Yeah. Yeah, really.
- Wow.

1275
01:41:19,192 --> 01:41:23,390
Yeah, it doesn't feel like "wow," Miles.
I really screwed up.

1276
01:41:23,495 --> 01:41:28,228
Yeah, you did.
But you had a life experience.

1277
01:41:32,671 --> 01:41:34,662
I can't believe how I treated you, Miles.

1278
01:41:34,773 --> 01:41:38,675
You know, you're my best friend,
and I really let you down.

1279
01:41:39,544 --> 01:41:42,638
I really let you down. I'm sorry.

1280
01:41:44,449 --> 01:41:48,977
And I'm happy for you, you know?
Winning the 2.09? That's great.

1281
01:41:50,355 --> 01:41:52,823
- Jill Taylor. Really?
- Yeah.

1282
01:41:55,360 --> 01:41:57,453
So let me get this straight.

1283
01:41:58,130 --> 01:42:01,293
Money, girls,

1284
01:42:02,467 --> 01:42:06,870
high-roller suites, clubs, Vegas.

1285
01:42:08,073 --> 01:42:13,101
Yeah, I think I probably would have
blown off the 2.09 Competition, too.

1286
01:42:16,648 --> 01:42:18,013
So we cool?

1287
01:42:19,651 --> 01:42:21,243
Yeah, we're cool.

1288
01:42:21,753 --> 01:42:24,449
But you better believe that
you're gonna make this up to me, big time.

1289
01:42:24,556 --> 01:42:25,818
All right.

1290
01:42:27,125 --> 01:42:29,252
So, what are you gonna do now?

1291
01:43:20,044 --> 01:43:21,875
What do you want, Ben?
This is an alumni dinner.

1292
01:43:21,979 --> 01:43:24,345
You need a diploma
to come to one of these.

1293
01:43:24,448 --> 01:43:26,848
Wait. Stupnitsky wants back in.

1294
01:43:33,057 --> 01:43:34,024
What?

1295
01:43:34,125 --> 01:43:38,255
Look, I've had some time
to think about what you said.

1296
01:43:40,131 --> 01:43:41,621
I want back in.

1297
01:43:42,600 --> 01:43:46,467
- Why now?
- Because I have nothing else.

1298
01:43:48,338 --> 01:43:51,535
All right, look, Ben. I'm not gonna lie to you.
You're good, you're very, very good.

1299
01:43:51,641 --> 01:43:55,805
But you did exactly what I told you not to.
You got emotional and then you got stupid.

1300
01:43:55,912 --> 01:43:59,609
Now you tell me why in the world
I'd ever get back in business with you.

1301
01:43:59,716 --> 01:44:04,176
Look, I know I should never have
disrespected you, all right? I know that.

1302
01:44:05,155 --> 01:44:07,123
With this facial recognition software,

1303
01:44:07,223 --> 01:44:10,420
our window of opportunity
is closing in on us.

1304
01:44:10,960 --> 01:44:14,623
Now, I need this, Micky.
I really, really need this.

1305
01:44:14,731 --> 01:44:19,862
Well, the take would have to be really, really
good to get me even vaguely interested.

1306
01:44:21,371 --> 01:44:26,673
Well, you know, that's why I was thinking
maybe you should be the other big player.

1307
01:44:28,078 --> 01:44:31,411
You know, two big players playing big?

1308
01:44:32,582 --> 01:44:35,915
Hey, slow down,
I haven't played in a long time, Ben.

1309
01:44:40,356 --> 01:44:41,948
But Fisher's out.

1310
01:44:42,826 --> 01:44:47,195
No one else on the team
can be the big player, can they?

1311
01:44:50,433 --> 01:44:53,834
And if we do well, if we do really well,

1312
01:44:54,604 --> 01:44:57,766
then you get your grades back,
get to Harvard Med,

1313
01:44:58,774 --> 01:45:01,299
and I might even get that sabbatical.

1314
01:45:02,311 --> 01:45:06,771
Well, amazing things can be done
from the inside, right?

1315
01:45:08,717 --> 01:45:11,413
Just went back to the head of the class.

1316
01:45:12,688 --> 01:45:14,553
I gotta go be social.

1317
01:45:19,928 --> 01:45:23,227
All right, now listen.
It's different out there this time.

1318
01:45:23,332 --> 01:45:26,199
The stakes are high
and it's more dangerous.

1319
01:45:26,735 --> 01:45:29,795
But the return is gonna be the biggest.

1320
01:45:31,106 --> 01:45:34,542
Now they know our faces,
so we're gonna wear disguises.

1321
01:45:34,776 --> 01:45:36,744
And we can't mess around.

1322
01:45:37,112 --> 01:45:38,579
I'm glad you're back with us, Micky.

1323
01:45:38,680 --> 01:45:40,580
Well, I couldn't let you guys
come back to this town

1324
01:45:40,682 --> 01:45:44,174
and not prove to Ben
that I can do more than just teach.

1325
01:45:45,020 --> 01:45:48,922
But as we've all said, this game
is about the past and the future,

1326
01:45:49,024 --> 01:45:52,084
and tonight we forget about the past.

1327
01:45:52,327 --> 01:45:54,192
We just focus on the future.

1328
01:45:54,296 --> 01:45:57,629
Right. This is our last time.

1329
01:45:58,033 --> 01:46:01,059
Now, we all know the drill if things get ugly.
We meet at the Fox Strip Club.

1330
01:46:01,170 --> 01:46:03,502
Nobody leaves this town alone.

1331
01:46:06,974 --> 01:46:08,874
Let's go make a killing.

1332
01:46:09,410 --> 01:46:10,775
All right.

1333
01:46:32,900 --> 01:46:35,368
Let's see what we can do with this.

1334
01:46:44,478 --> 01:46:48,539
Seems like I'm having one of those days,
you know what I mean, Jim?

1335
01:46:50,218 --> 01:46:52,345
I'm bringing all the luck today.
I'm just bringing it all.

1336
01:46:52,453 --> 01:46:56,913
Anyone who's in any kind of contact
with me is getting so much luck today.

1337
01:47:08,569 --> 01:47:10,730
Winner, winner, chicken dinner! There it is.

1338
01:47:10,838 --> 01:47:14,274
Thank you. God, I love this town.
I love this game.

1339
01:47:15,076 --> 01:47:18,374
And, Jim, I might even love you.

1340
01:47:28,188 --> 01:47:30,383
Hey, you mind if I sit down?

1341
01:47:44,404 --> 01:47:45,462
What's your name?

1342
01:47:45,572 --> 01:47:48,700
Shane? I'm about to change your luck.
It's gonna become mine.

1343
01:47:48,808 --> 01:47:51,038
There you go, give me it all.

1344
01:48:01,087 --> 01:48:02,281
There you go.

1345
01:48:05,058 --> 01:48:06,821
Thank you. Thank you.

1346
01:48:11,564 --> 01:48:13,794
Such a shame, Shane!

1347
01:48:14,768 --> 01:48:16,827
Okay, I'm supposed to double, right?

1348
01:48:16,936 --> 01:48:21,270
- Is this your first time, darling?
- I've been winning and losing for hours.

1349
01:48:21,374 --> 01:48:23,467
Well, that's all right.
I've been winning and losing for years.

1350
01:48:36,789 --> 01:48:38,313
What the hell kind of streak
are you on, boy?

1351
01:48:38,424 --> 01:48:41,086
This never happens, this never happens.

1352
01:48:54,139 --> 01:48:55,936
I'm just gonna have to split those tens.

1353
01:48:56,041 --> 01:48:57,599
- Splitting tens.
- Splitting tens!

1354
01:48:57,710 --> 01:48:58,844
- Split tens!
- Again!

1355
01:48:58,844 --> 01:48:59,572
- Split tens!
- Again!

1356
01:49:22,501 --> 01:49:25,470
- Thank you, ma'am.
- Give me the chips, Blanca.

1357
01:49:26,705 --> 01:49:28,570
Give me the chips!
Come on, give me the chips, Blanca.

1358
01:49:28,674 --> 01:49:31,575
Come on, just give me the chips!

1359
01:49:31,677 --> 01:49:35,807
- My bus has to leave right away.
- I gotta walk my dog.

1360
01:49:35,914 --> 01:49:38,473
- I'm sorry we're making such a mess.
- Go, go, go, go, go.

1361
01:49:38,583 --> 01:49:41,643
Nice to see you. Have a good night, darling.

1362
01:49:47,191 --> 01:49:48,488
This way!

1363
01:49:59,704 --> 01:50:00,796
Go.

1364
01:50:15,153 --> 01:50:16,518
This way!

1365
01:50:22,427 --> 01:50:24,418
Come on, Jill. Come on!

1366
01:50:34,338 --> 01:50:36,932
Go that way. Throw me the chips.
Come on, we gotta separate.

1367
01:50:37,041 --> 01:50:39,908
Give me the chips, I'll meet you at Fox's.

1368
01:50:45,983 --> 01:50:47,575
Go, go, go, go!

1369
01:50:58,528 --> 01:51:00,189
Come on, come on.

1370
01:51:03,300 --> 01:51:04,858
Move, move, move!

1371
01:51:09,039 --> 01:51:10,301
Come on.

1372
01:51:11,441 --> 01:51:13,033
Go, go, this way.

1373
01:51:25,021 --> 01:51:26,852
All right, let's go.

1374
01:51:34,931 --> 01:51:37,422
Go, go, go, go! Airport!

1375
01:51:55,986 --> 01:51:57,613
<i>I never saw Micky Rosa after that.</i>

1376
01:52:02,691 --> 01:52:03,953
Oh, God.

1377
01:52:05,060 --> 01:52:07,324
But I think I wanna see him now.

1378
01:52:08,397 --> 01:52:10,865
And I want you to make that happen.

1379
01:52:15,137 --> 01:52:17,571
I don't work for Micky anymore.

1380
01:52:20,576 --> 01:52:22,009
Come on, kid.

1381
01:52:23,846 --> 01:52:27,612
Your picture's all over the database.
Your Vegas gig is done.

1382
01:52:28,651 --> 01:52:30,585
But I will give you one night.

1383
01:52:30,686 --> 01:52:33,746
And I can guarantee
that you won't be bothered.

1384
01:52:34,657 --> 01:52:38,423
You'll make a killing, and you'll keep it all.

1385
01:52:41,497 --> 01:52:42,691
Listen.

1386
01:52:44,266 --> 01:52:45,733
My name's Cole.

1387
01:52:47,303 --> 01:52:48,827
Cole Williams.

1388
01:52:50,739 --> 01:52:53,139
You just bring me Micky Rosa, kid.

1389
01:52:53,442 --> 01:52:55,467
I'll take care of the rest.

1390
01:52:58,013 --> 01:53:00,948
Son of a bitch.

1391
01:53:43,591 --> 01:53:45,354
Who the hell are you?

1392
01:54:08,216 --> 01:54:11,379
Ben. Good job.

1393
01:54:12,453 --> 01:54:17,516
You'll be glad to know I'm gonna have a talk
with your professor, and that MIT thing?

1394
01:54:17,725 --> 01:54:19,818
It's gonna work out for you.

1395
01:54:21,395 --> 01:54:22,953
So that's it?

1396
01:54:24,398 --> 01:54:27,162
- That's it.
- All right.

1397
01:54:28,135 --> 01:54:29,830
Oh, Dr. Campbell?

1398
01:54:31,171 --> 01:54:34,140
They don't have pensions
in my line of work.

1399
01:54:34,474 --> 01:54:36,374
And the software does
what it's supposed to do.

1400
01:54:36,476 --> 01:54:40,378
And I been chasing Micky Rosa around here
for too damn long.

1401
01:54:41,615 --> 01:54:43,879
I'm looking at some retirement.

1402
01:54:45,786 --> 01:54:47,253
Leave the bag.

1403
01:54:49,322 --> 01:54:51,620
No. No, no, no, no.

1404
01:54:51,725 --> 01:54:56,219
I need this money. You have no idea
what I went through to get this money.

1405
01:54:56,329 --> 01:55:01,323
I know, kid, but you're gonna figure out
how to get everything you want in this life,

1406
01:55:01,435 --> 01:55:03,164
'cause you're smart.

1407
01:55:04,738 --> 01:55:09,266
So, you're gonna leave the bag.

1408
01:55:14,314 --> 01:55:18,910
Ben, give him the bag. Give him the bag.
It doesn't matter. Give him the bag.

1409
01:55:27,761 --> 01:55:29,558
I knew you were smart.

1410
01:55:48,414 --> 01:55:51,144
<i>I had a 1590 on my SAT.</i>

1411
01:55:51,250 --> 01:55:53,309
<i>I got a 44 on my MCATs.</i>

1412
01:55:53,819 --> 01:55:56,947
<i>And I have a 4.0 GPA from MIT.</i>

1413
01:55:57,056 --> 01:55:59,524
<i>I thought I had my life mapped out.</i>

1414
01:56:01,427 --> 01:56:02,519
<i>But then I remembered</i>

1415
01:56:02,628 --> 01:56:06,086
<i>what my Nonlinear Equations professor
once told me,</i>

1416
01:56:06,632 --> 01:56:09,863
<i>"Always account for variable change."</i>

1417
01:56:11,670 --> 01:56:13,194
Hello, Micky.

1418
01:56:14,907 --> 01:56:16,738
Look, I got money in Boston.
A hundred grand.

1419
01:56:16,842 --> 01:56:18,867
I'll give it to you.
Just let me walk away. I'll walk away.

1420
01:56:18,978 --> 01:56:22,038
I don't want your money, Micky.
I don't need it.

1421
01:56:27,853 --> 01:56:30,651
But I know someone
who might be interested.

1422
01:56:31,023 --> 01:56:35,119
He's good with numbers, too.
He works for the IRS.

1423
01:56:43,935 --> 01:56:45,994
<i>I let down my good friends.</i>

1424
01:56:46,671 --> 01:56:51,608
<i>But as it turns out,
they weren't too bad at simple math either.</i>

1425
01:57:17,435 --> 01:57:19,995
<i>I scored the prettiest girl in school.</i>

1426
01:57:23,474 --> 01:57:26,102
<i>I got beaten down
by an old-school Vegas thug</i>

1427
01:57:26,211 --> 01:57:29,408
<i>who was having trouble
